Full Description: eQuorum has focused on solving complex document management problems for hundreds of organizations in the manufacturing, engineering, utilities and AECO (Architectural, Engineering, Construction and Owner) arenas where customers seek to better organize documents, save time, and enhance collaboration. The privately-held company was spun out of Byers Engineering Company (as CADNET Corporation) in 1996 after operating as an independent profit center since 1987. Byers Engineering Company (www.byers.com), founded in 1971, is a large engineering firm with approximately 1,200 employees. eQuorum and Byers Engineering have common ownership, with Ken Byers serving as Chairman of eQuorum’s Board of Directors. The company’s name was changed to eQuorum Corporation in 1999 after a merger with Virginia-based Image Machines Corporation. CADNET was well-known for its productivity-boosting wide format printing solutions, and Image Machines was recognized for its document management, and fast editing and imaging solutions. By leveraging the integrated products from both companies, customers have greater control and flexibility over the management, collaboration, distribution, and printing of their business documents, including complex images and large format engineering drawings. Organizations that rely on engineering content need a better way to securely and simply manage documents. That’s why they turn to eQuorum’s comprehensive, yet easy-to-use solutions to manage their data - from design to manufacturing to production.

Description: QP Semiconductor is a fabless semiconductor company.
Headquarters Regions: San Francisco Bay Area, Silicon Valley, West Coast
Full Description: QP Semiconductor, Inc., a fabless semiconductor company, designs, manufactures, re-engineers, and provides integrated circuits for military and aerospace industries. It offers analog products ranging from op amps and comparators to voltage regulators; and logic products, including line drivers and receivers. The company also provides EPROM products to support various Hi Rel and military applications; FIFO products; microcontrollers; microprocessor and peripherals; programmable logic devices; BiPolar PROM products; CMOS PROM products; and SRAM products. In addition, it offers replacement hermetic parts for diminished manufacturing sources and end of life products. The company sells its products through representatives and distributors in North America, France, Belgium, Spain, Germany, Austria, Switzerland, Hong Kong, India, Italy, Israel, Japan, Turkey, the United Kingdom, and Ireland. QP Semiconductor, Inc. was formerly known as QP Labs, Inc. and changed its name to QP Semiconductor, Inc. in 2003. The company was founded in 1985 and is headquartered in Santa Clara, California. The company has internal test and burn-in facility in Santa Clara, California; and Bangkok, Thailand, as well as sales locations in the Eastern and Western United States, British Columbia, Canada, Europe, and Asia. As of October 10, 2008, QP Semiconductor, Inc. operates as a subsidiary of e2v Technologies plc.
